reviewText: I did not know Gypsy Vanner horses existed til I watched this show and I came away from it wanting one. I've never wanted a horse in my life as I've never had the space or means to take care of them, however after watching this film.. I want one even tho I still don't have the space or means.  If you are a horse lover this it definitely a film you will enjoy.. if you're not a horse lover, watch this and marvel at a breed of horse that not only is a powerhouse, but enjoyable and lovable as well. Now that I've seen this film I've the desire to seek them out when possible.

reviewText: Only 60 years ago Gypsies, or Romany, decided to begin selectively breeding their horses that pulled their wagons to create a new breed.  They succeeded beyond all imagination, turning ordinary cart horses of no particular distinction into magnificent creatures that enchant and beguile upon first sight.  Oh, how I'd love a couple to start my own horse farm!  This film is "...an advertisement..."as another reviewer carped.  Well, of course it is!  What would one expect?  And yes, Vanners are not for peasants like myself, forever chained to the social class of the lower sorts.  Owning a Vanner is expensive.  Very.  Strictly for the very, very wealthy.  As a breed, they're just getting started in this country.  But, oh, would I love to sit on the fence and watch as some ran by!  Vanners are the one thing I can think of that the rich are doing that are enhancing life on this planet rather than destroying it.  Their soft eyes and friendly manners shine as they prance by, glorious manes, tails, and fetlocks rippling and flowing in their self-made breeze.  Vanners are an art form in their own right.

reviewText: This is a well made documentary about a rare horse breed.  It is a lift to the spirit to see these animals in action.  One of the better parts of this film shows an owner washing and cleaning up the massive feathering, mane, and tail hair on the horse.  The horses are beautiful and have a great personality but they do require a good deal of maintenance to keep fit.  We also get a little history on the animal and see it in its native Ireland.  A really fun forty minute film for anyone who loves equines.
